  The sound of heavy hydraulics depressurizing cuts through the howling wind. At the edge of a massive, shadowed canyon of rusted steel and black glass, the older Tarbit drops to one knee. His hands---wrapped in tape and scarred from hot soldering iron burns---work the release valves on his heavy exo-striders.
  
  "Drop the striders, kid," the veteran says, not looking up as he tightens the strap of the cyberdeck across his chest. "We go the rest of the way on our own joints. They'll slow us down if we have to run."

  "But..." the rookie protests. "It's a kilometer to the inner gates. What if the defense drones are active?"

  "If the defense drones hear the whine of those reg-motors, you won't have time to run," the veteran replies. He points a taped finger at the dark, geometric skyline. "You see that? That's not a datacenter. That's a Martas. An Old World colony. And it is very much awake."
  
  "I thought you said they built these places to keep people safe."
  
  "They did." The older Tarbit walks to the edge of the ridge. "The AI running that Martas had zero-latency biometric recognition. It was perfect. Right up until the Global Warning. When the networks fractured, the main servers went down. It defaulted into absolute lockdown. It went Read-Only. Nobody had admin privileges anymore."

  The rookie steps up beside him. "So?"

  "So, think about the data logic, kid. You survive the collapse. You have a son. But when you go to the terminal to register him, you can't. The database is locked. You can't write to it. And the next time your kid crawls into a camera's line of sight? The AI cross-references the database. It doesn't find him."
  
  The rookie's eyes widen.
  
  "To the AI, your son isn't a resident. He's an unregistered anomaly. An external threat. The system didn't turn evil. It just executed its code. That's why we move quiet, and that's why we don't speak English in there. If we trip a sensor, we have exactly three seconds to hardwire a terminal and speak Arta faster than the AI can pull the trigger."

  The veteran types a fast, blind command on his deck. A green light flashes.
  
  #text(font: "monospace", weight: "bold")[NI fir .] _(We move)_.
  
  "Stay in my shadow," he whispers.
]

